text=:Category: Varia%0a:Essential: {Category.Varia$:essential}%0a:Title: Personality Shift When Switching Languages%0a:Author: MarkC%0a:Section: F%0a:Completed: 08.05.2021 - 20:59%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210512-124946-396660#%0a* [-12.05.2021 - 05:49-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210512-124946-396660#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHow changing languages can affect personality%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aStudies have shown that for multilingual people, what language they are using has an effect on their personality. The concept is generally referred to “frame-shifting” or “frame-switching” and refers to a shift in cultural specific mental frames when multicultural/multilingual people switch between languages.  This shift in cultural mental frame can refer to a shift in personality, identity, values, etc. For example, a study involving a group of Hispanic women found that the women viewed themselves as more assertive when speaking Spanish compared to English, and outsiders perceived them as more self-sufficient and extroverted when speaking Spanish.%0a%0aSources:%0a%0ahttps://open.maricopa.edu/culturepsychology/chapter/cultural-frame-switching/%0a%0ahttps://www.reuters.com/article/us-languages-personalities/switching-languages-can-also-switch-personality-study-idUSSP4652020080624%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
