diff:1620532773:1620532773:=1,52d0%0a%3c :Category: Varia%0a%3c :Essential: {Category.Varia$:essential}%0a%3c :Title: Personality Shift When Switching Languages%0a%3c :Author: MarkC%0a%3c :Section: F%0a%3c :Completed: 08.05.2021 - 20:59%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c Summary: \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c How changing languages can affect personality%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Studies have shown that for multilingual people, what language they are using has an effect on their personality. The concept is generally referred to “frame-shifting” or “frame-switching” and refers to a shift in cultural specific mental frames when multicultural/multilingual people switch between languages.  This shift in cultural mental frame can refer to a shift in personality, identity, values, etc. For example, a study involving a group of Hispanic women found that the women viewed themselves as more assertive when speaking Spanish compared to English, and outsiders perceived them as more self-sufficient and extroverted when speaking Spanish.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c %0a%3c https://open.maricopa.edu/culturepsychology/chapter/cultural-frame-switching/%0a%3c %0a%3c https://www.reuters.com/article/us-languages-personalities/switching-languages-can-also-switch-personality-study-idUSSP4652020080624%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
